<p>
We were working on auto today and have a problem when trying to get a coral from the coral station. We have a default command, <code>s_Intake.setDefaultCommand(new RunCommand(() -&gt; s_Intake.autoIntake(), s_Intake));</code>, which is supposed to always run the intake wheels until the beam break sensor is blocked, unless we’re scoring coral. However, the wheels just seem to be spinning but not stopping when the sensor is blocked.</p>
<p>Subsystems which do things in their <code>periodic</code> functions seem to work fine (like elevator and LEDs, which light up based on that same beam break) but this one does not. Looking at the past couple years I think this also our first default command which does not just stop a motor or which requires joystick input to operate (like swerve or climber arms).</p>
<p>Any suggestions? Should we just specifically call <code>autoIntake</code> from path planner when we want to use it?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":3,"updated_at":"2025-03-02T01:48:18.006Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":30,"reads":75,"readers_count":74,"score":165.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":493811,"topic_slug":"question-about-default-commands-during-auto","display_username":"Christopher149","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/SuperiorRoboworksTeam857/2025Reefscape/blob/main/src/main/java/frc/robot/RobotContainer.java","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"2025Reefscape/src/main/java/frc/robot/RobotContainer.java at main · SuperiorRoboworksTeam857/2025Reefscape · GitHub","clicks":3}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":14984,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"FRC857 lead mentor / FTC10723+13284+15270 lead mentor"},"post_url":"/t/question-about-default-commands-during-auto/493811/1","custom_user_title":"FRC857 lead mentor / FTC10723+13284+15270 lead mentor","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true,"can_vote":false},{"id":3544590,"name":"Max Morehead","username":"Max_Morehead","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/max_morehead/{size}/231937_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-02T02:28:35.974Z","cooked":"<p>This is caused by a detail about how the command system works. CommandGroups require all the subsystems of their constituent commands. Then, from the Scheduler’s point of view, all it only sees the outer most command group, which requires many subsystems.</p>
<p>In auto, all your commands run as part of a <code>SequentialCommand</code>, which requires all the commands that are part of it. I assume your pathplanner auto includes the score command, which requires the intake. So, while the auto is running there will be a command running that requires the intake, so the default command will never run.</p>
<p>The simplest way to fix this is to make the score command a proxy command when you pass it to pathplanner. A proxy command can be include in a CommandGroup but not have the commandgroup require the requirements of the command (the way it works is a little more complicated than that, and I highly recommend you read the docs on this, including its important caveats). So just add <code>.asProxy()</code> when you pass your score command to PP. (Importantly, if you make one command in a group a proxy, all commands in that group which which require the same subsystems as the proxy must be proxies as well).</p>
